%I A395181 #14 Apr 20 2026 23:51:10
%S A395181 1,3,8,12,24,48,72,96,120,144,168,192,216,288,360,384,504,528,576,600,
%T A395181 648,768,840,864,960,1080,1152,1344,1368,1440,1536,1584,1680,1728,
%U A395181 1800,1848,1944,2016,2208,2304,2352,2520,2808,2880,3072,3456,3480,3720,4032,4104,4224,4320,4488,4608
%N A395181 Values taken by Jordan's totient function J_2, A007434.
%C A395181 Under a multiplication which is not completely multiplicative, for a quadratic number ring which is a UFD, the full set of values of its Euler totient function can be produced from the set {(p-1)*p^(r-1), (q^2-1)*(q^2)^(s-1)} = {phi(p^r), J_2(q^s)} for all primes p and q where p is either ramified or split, and q is inert. For the totient values in Z (A002202), this initial set is {(p-1)p^(e-1)} for all primes p. The present sequence contains those values generated solely by the Jordan totient function J_2 for all prime powers q^s.
%H A395181 Miles Englezou, <a href="/A395181/b395181.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..2317</a>
%e A395181 3 is a term since (2^2-1)*(2^2)^0 = 3.
%e A395181 8 is a term since (3^2-1)*(3^2)^0 = 8.
%e A395181 12 is a term since (2^2-1)*(2^2)^1 = 12.
%e A395181 144 is a term since 3 and 48 are terms, gcd(3, 48) = 1, and 3*48 = 144.
%o A395181 (PARI) lst(lim) = my(S = Set([1])); forprime(p = 2, lim, my(L = List()); for(e = 1, oo, my(v = (p^2)^(e-1) * (p^2 - 1)); if(v > lim, break); listput(L, v)); my(T = Set(S)); for(i = 1, #S, for(j = 1, #L, my(v = S[i] * L[j]); if(v <= lim, T = setunion(T, Set([v]))))); S = T); S
%Y A395181 Cf. A002202, A007434.
%K A395181 nonn,new
%O A395181 1,2
%A A395181 _Miles Englezou_, Apr 15 2026
